snippet.textDisplay:
As a BMW fan and owner, the video doesn't show a single ounce of understanding of these luxury brands, clearly they haven't done enough research. Most of the problems laid out in the second half of the video are the identical challenges for OTHER competing brands.


The comments are more ridiculous, mostly by ignorant non-owners. I see the number one response is about "grill size". This is non sense, look at the industry as a whole. Look at how big Lexus grills are now (Especially F sport models), look how big Benz's logo got (and the LED lighted option, which Mazda copied).


My take on BMW's biggest failure in the recent decade is actually about leasing. I've always bought my BMW and strongly believe the amount of leases is hurting the brand image. A significant portion of luxury cars that are leased are more basic models, indicating that consumers just want the brand prestige and don't actually care for a lot of the features that make the car better, as a response manufacturers keep introducing lower and lower end models. Think BMW's X1, X2, 1/2 series, MB's A class, CLA class, etc etc.

snippet.textDisplay: Are you kidding me? BMW doesnt have too few models...they have TOO MANY!  My God you cant even keep track of them anymore. They've even watered down the M badge by putting it on just about everything thats not even an M car. Then BMW made the absolutely disastrous decisiont to completely relabel their entire car lineup by splitting coupes and sedans into even and odd numbers. No reason to do this other than too many idiots in the room trying to feel important.  And then theres the nomenclature. X-Drive this, M340 that, on and on it goes.  Marketing idiots are running the asylum. They need to go back to 3-5-7 series. If they want an 8 series then so be it because thats also historical.  We DONT need an M3 and M4 to separate a coupe and sedan for christ sakes...we were building M3 coupes and sedands as far back as 1997 -- this is not difficult to understand. And why this X-Drive crap?  How about just X like BMW used to do it in the old days to describe anyone with AWD like the E30 325ix??  Why are you making this more complicated than it needs to be?  People are avoiding BMW because its just too much work anymore to bother figuring out the difference in any of these cars. And it doesnt help that the new 3-series is as big as the old 5-series. And it doesnt help that the kidney grilles have become so bastardized that they dont even shout BMW anymore. THIS IS THE SINGLE MOST IMPORTANT ELEMENT OF ANY BMW DESIGN LANGUAGE -- THE GRILLES!!  When the average person thinks of BMW this is what they think of.....the smaller rectangle grilles on an E30 or E28.  Now the grilles arent even rectangle. The E46 started abusing the shape. Now the shape looks like some Chinese car company. Not rectangle, not square, they have swoopy corners and curves, and my God on the SUVs they are just a giant monstrosity.  BMW ran away from all the things people associated with BMW -- simple pleasure and design. Even the rear passenger window "notch J hook" has gotten bastardized.  They need to completely simplify their lineups have to 3-5-7 series with just a few models in each one with simpler naming conventions. And then bring in a guy that studies the BMW designs of the 80s and 90s and incorporates those back into the new designs. Until then everything BMW is churning out just looks like the Buick down the street. When you are spending $80,000 thats a problem.

snippet.textDisplay:
I wrote about this a few years ago.

I feel as if once BMW really mastered the HMI - their iDrive system - they were scared to mess it up. They were the best, by far, at it's time. The best user experience and the safest.
But instead of plowing forward to continue to lead that space, they became content and were scared of change.

Some may argue that just lacking innovation on the HMI/Entertainment front couldn't do so much damage, but remember that the iDrive system is a core element of the car; many design decisions are based around it.

Also; people like "new". I did not see the logic in making gran coupe versions of the 3 and 4 series carry the same name except for adding gran coupe. A new name would of allowed them further expansion. The "gran coupe" stuff was just confusing. Also, one gran coupe is enough. Not much difference between the 3 and 4 to begin with.

Lastly, the exterior design of the 2 door coupes look almost identical to one 10 years old. Why buy a new one when literally nobody could even tell the difference. Same iDrive system, and same body for the most part.


--

snippet.textDisplay: I had a 2008 760Li, the flagship of BMW . I bought it used in 2013 with 41000 miles on it. This model was introduced in 2002 as 2003 model. In six years BMW had ample opportunity to get the bugs out. I had so many issues with that car and most of them component failures. Three months ago I took it to the BMW service center and told them the car was idling rough. They changed many parts and the bill was $2100 and they could not fix the problem. They were guessing that it was the fuel pump which was priced at $4000 installed. This particular dealer has a huge turnover in their mechanic's roster. There is no one who knows how to fix anything. They just change parts. Making long story short, I sold that car for $5000 with 80800 miles on it. When new it was $136500. I called the BMW north America headquarters and got no help. I have been a BMW customer for 31 years.
